{"title":"Semantically Grounded Object Matching for Robust Robotic Scene Rearrangement","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"In goal-image-conditioned robotic rearrangement, matching objects between the current scene and the goal image degrades under visual shifts (pose, background) and typically assumes the exact same object instances appear in both images, which is impractical for real deployments.","method":"Introduce a visual-semantic matching approach that leverages CLIP to incorporate object semantics into matching. After instance segmentation, crops from source and target images are encoded with CLIP’s image encoder, and a set of K text prompts (semantic labels) are encoded with CLIP’s text encoder. Classification matrices C_s and C_t are formed via cosine similarities between visual and semantic embeddings, and the final source–target similarity is computed as S = C_t C_s^T, followed by assignment via argmax or the Hungarian algorithm. Two practical variants are used: CLIP-SemFeat-K (all K labels) and CLIP-SemFeat-N (only labels known to be present). Lightweight prompt engineering is applied to improve zero-shot alignment. This semantic projection enables robust cross-instance matching and outperforms purely visual baselines in LVIS 8-way/20-way settings (e.g., 58.8%/40.1% vs 50.6%/35.5% for ResNet50-G)."},{"problem":"There is a lack of controlled evaluation isolating how object-matching methods fail as visual shift increases, and no standard setup to study cross-instance matching for rearrangement.","method":"Provide a controlled analysis across curated same-instance splits of the APC dataset (Easy/Medium/Hard/Hardest) to systematically vary viewpoint, pose, and background, and construct synthetic N-way cross-instance matching tasks using LVIS. Results show that purely visual features (e.g., ResNet50, AlexNet, color histograms) degrade sharply with increasing shift and across instances, while CLIP-based visual-semantic matching degrades less in APC and 